📌 Overview

This project provides an infrastructure-as-code solution for deploying a highly available 
Amazon EKS (Elastic Kubernetes Service) cluster across two Availability Zones using AWS 
CloudFormation. The setup includes an EC2 Bastion Host to provide secure SSM access for 
managing the cluster and related resources. A private EC2 bastion host provides secure SSM 
and AWS SSO access for managing the cluster and related resources. Deployment is handled by 
an AWS CodeBuild pipeline — no access keys are ever stored or passed as parameters.

🛠️ Features

    🏗️ Deploys a fully managed EKS cluster on AWS

    🌐 Spans across two Availability Zones for high availability

    🔐 EC2 Bastion Host for secure management access with ALB for GitLab access 

    🔄 Supports cluster upgrades and scalability

    🧩 Modular CloudFormation templates for reusability

    🏃 Automated deployment of Kubernets cluster, monitoring namespace, alerting, ingress 
    and application for complete end to end automation. 

    🧳 EFS-backed persistent storage for the database

    🖼️ ECR for container image storage

🧱 Architecture

    EKS Cluster

        Control plane managed by AWS

        Worker nodes in private subnets across 2 AZs

        2 Node groups, one for monitoring and the other for the application and core Kube 
            functions 

    VPC

        Custom VPC with public, private and protected subnets

        NAT Gateway in each AZ

    Bastion Host

        ARM (Graviton) in a private subnet

        Accesses the EKS cluster via an attached IAM role — no access keys

        Authenticates to AWS using AWS SSO (`aws sso login --profile doggy-admin`)

        KMS-encrypted EBS volume

    Storage

        EFS file system mounted to the private subnets for persistent database storage

    ECR

        Elastic Container Registry for storing application container images

    ALB

        Application Load Balancer in public subnets, forwarding traffic to the GitLab instance running on the bastion

🚀 Deployment

    You must have some things set up before you can run the start up script 
        1. Install the AWS CLI (steps vary by OS — see the [AWS docs](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/getting-started-install.html)).

        2. **Set up IAM Identity Center** (if you haven't already):

            1. In the AWS console, go to **IAM Identity Center** and enable it.
            2. Create a user for yourself and assign it the `AdministratorAccess` permission set on your account.
            3. Note the **AWS access portal URL** shown on the IAM Identity Center dashboard (it looks like `https://d-xxxxxxxxxx.awsapps.com/start`).

        3 **Configure the local profile:**

```bash
aws configure sso
```

This will prompt you for:

| Prompt | Value |
|---|---|
| SSO session name | `doggy-session` |
| SSO start URL | your IAM Identity Center portal URL |
| SSO region | `us-east-1` |
| SSO registration scopes | `sso:account:access` |
| Account ID | your 12-digit AWS account ID |
| Role name | `AdministratorAccess` |
| Default region | `us-east-1` |
| Default output format | `json` |
| Profile name | `doggy-admin` |

This writes a profile called `doggy-admin` to `~/.aws/config` — the same profile name used on the bastion, so the mental model is consistent throughout.

        4. **Log in before running any commands:**

```bash
aws sso login --profile doggy-admin
```

This opens a browser to complete the SSO login. Tokens are cached locally and valid for the session duration configured in IAM Identity Center (typically 8–12 hours).

        5. S3 bucket for nested templates

The CloudFormation package command uploads nested templates to S3. Create the bucket if it doesn't exist:

```bash
aws s3 mb s3://doggy-template-build-terminal --region us-east-1 --profile doggy-admin
```

        6. OpenAI API key in Secrets Manager

The alerting pod uses OpenAI. Create an account at [https://openai.com/api/](https://openai.com/api/), generate an API key, and load a small amount of credit (a couple of dollars is more than enough for a demo).

Store the key in AWS Secrets Manager. The secret should store the key as a single plaintext string (or as a key/value pair with key `key`):

```bash
aws secretsmanager create-secret \
  --name openai-key \
  --secret-string '{"openai-key":"<your-openai-key>"}' \
  --region us-east-1 \
  --profile doggy-admin
```

Note the ARN that is returned — you will pass it as `OpenAISecret` during deployment.

---

### Deploy

```bash
git clone https://github.com/DoggyApp/CloudFormationArchitecture.git
cd CloudFormationArchitecture
```

Package nested templates to S3:

```bash
aws cloudformation package \
  --template-file master.yaml \
  --s3-bucket doggy-template-build-terminal \
  --output-template-file packaged-root-template.yaml \
  --profile doggy-admin
```

Validate the packaged template:

```bash
aws cloudformation validate-template \
  --template-body file://packaged-root-template.yaml \
  --profile doggy-admin
```

Deploy the stack:

```bash
aws cloudformation deploy \
  --template-file packaged-root-template.yaml \
  --stack-name doggy-stack \
  --capabilities CAPABILITY_NAMED_IAM \
  --region us-east-1 \
  --parameter-overrides \
    Email=<your-alert-email> \
    AWSID=<your-aws-account-id> \
    OpenAISecret=<arn-of-openai-secret> \
  --profile doggy-admin
```

No access keys are passed as stack parameters. The bastion host authenticates to AWS using the IAM role attached to the instance and AWS SSO — credentials are never stored in the template or passed on the command line.

The full stack — EKS cluster, bastion, EFS, ALB, ECR, and all supporting resources — takes around 30 minutes to come up. Check for the mgmt instance in EC2 intances, it will take a further 10 minutes for Python 10 to install, you will know that it is complete when you login and the python environment is present (shown in the terminal as (python 10 <user> $)). 

---

### Alternatively: deploy via CodeBuild

The `buildspec.yml` in this repo is designed to run the package, validate, and deploy steps inside an AWS CodeBuild project. CodeBuild runs under its own IAM service role, so no access keys are needed at all. The pipeline reads environment variables (`EMAIL`, `AWS_ID`) and pulls the OpenAI secret ARN directly from Secrets Manager.

---

### After deployment — managing the cluster

Connect to the bastion using SSM Session Manager:

```bash
aws ssm start-session --target <mgmt-instance-id> --profile doggy-admin
```

The bastion's `.bashrc` exports `AWS_PROFILE=doggy-admin` and immediately runs `aws sso login --profile doggy-admin` on login, so the SSO flow completes in the terminal before you run anything. This is the same profile used locally — the bastion SSO config mirrors what `aws configure sso` set up on your machine.

Several shortcut functions are available in `.bashrc`:

| Command | What it does |
|---|---|
| `setadmin` | Runs the Ansible playbook to grant admin access to the cluster and removes the pipeline itself (the creating entity) from the RBAC|
| `setupkube` | Runs the full Ansible setup: monitoring, alerting, ingress, application |
| `setupgit` | Runs the Ansible playbook to configure GitLab |
| `setkube` | Alias — updates kubeconfig for the EKS cluster |
| `teardown` | Deletes the entire environment including SNS subscriptions |

> **Warning:** Run `teardown` only after confirming your SNS subscription. If you tear down before confirming, the unconfirmed subscription cannot be deleted and will linger for 2–5 days until AWS garbage-collects it.


Contiue on to Kubenetes Architecture for the next steps in the deployment process. 
---

🛠️ Troubleshooting

Open the CloudFormation console in AWS and navigate to your stack. Clicking on a failed nested stack and selecting **Events** shows which resource failed and the error message at the top of the event list. The most common causes are permission errors on the CodeBuild or EC2 IAM roles.

---

🔐 Security

    🔒 Worker nodes and the bastion are placed in private subnets with no public IP addresses.
    🔒 The bastion security group blocks all inbound traffic; access is exclusively through AWS Systems Manager (SSM), which requires no open ports.
    🔒 The EKS cluster security group only accepts TCP traffic originating from the bastion security group.
    🔒 The bastion IAM role grants only what is needed: `eks:DescribeCluster`, `eks:AccessKubernetesApi`, `sts:GetCallerIdentity` scoped to the specific cluster ARN, plus `AmazonSSMManagedInstanceCore`.
    🔒 No access keys are passed into the stack. The bastion authenticates to AWS using its attached IAM role and AWS SSO.
    🔒 The OpenAI API key is stored in AWS Secrets Manager and accessed at runtime by ARN — it is never stored in code or passed as a plaintext parameter.
    🔒 EBS volumes on the bastion are encrypted with a KMS customer-managed key.
    🔒 IAM Identity Center (SSO) is used for all human access — locally and on the bastion. No long-lived access keys are created at any point in the setup or deployment process.
    🔒 IAM roles are used for all service access (CodeBuild, EC2 instance profile).
    🔒 MFA is enforced through IAM Identity Center.
